Project Description – Image classification using CNNs in Keras

Data Description:¶

You are provided with a dataset of images of plant seedlings at various stages of grown. Each image has a filename that is its unique id. The dataset comprises 12 plant species. The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo.

Normalize and Reshape Data¶

  • We must normalize our data as it is always required in neural network models
  • We can achieve this by dividing the RGB codes with 255 (which is the maximum RGB code minus the minimum RGB code)
  • We need normalize X_train, X_test and X_val
  • Finally, ensure that the values are float so that we can get decimal points after division
In [63]:
X_train = X_train.astype('float32')
X_test = X_test.astype('float32')
X_val = X_val.astype('float32')

X_train /= 255
X_test /= 255
X_val /= 255

One-hot encode the class vector¶

  • convert class vectors (integers) to binary class matrix
  • convert y_train, y_test and y_val
  • number of classes: 12
  • we are doing this to use categorical_crossentropy as loss
In [68]:
from tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical

y_train = to_categorical(y_train, num_classes=12)
y_test = to_categorical(y_test, num_classes=12)
y_val = to_categorical(y_val, num_classes=12)

Set the CNN Model¶

In [71]:
# Set the CNN model

batch_size = None

model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu", input_shape=X_train.shape[1:]))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))

model.add(layers.GlobalMaxPooling2D())
model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
model.add(layers.Dense(12, activation="softmax"))

model.summary()

In [75]:
#Adding Early stopping callback to the fit function is going to stop the training,
#if the val_loss is not going to change even '0.001' for more than 10 continous epochs
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', min_delta=0.001, patience=10)

#Adding Model Checkpoint callback to the fit function is going to save the weights whenever val_loss achieves a new low value. 
#Hence saving the best weights occurred during training

model_checkpoint =  ModelCheckpoint('cifar_cnn_checkpoint_{epoch:02d}_loss{val_loss:.4f}.h5',
                                                           monitor='val_loss',
                                                           verbose=1,
                                                           save_best_only=True,
                                                           save_weights_only=True,
                                                           mode='auto',
                                                           period=1)

WARNING:tensorflow:`period` argument is deprecated. Please use `save_freq` to specify the frequency in number of batches seen.

Fit the Model - Validate against validation data¶

In [77]:
history = model.fit(X_train,
                    y_train,
                    batch_size=batch_size,
                    epochs=epochs,
                    validation_data=(X_val, y_val),
                    shuffle=True,
                    verbose=1,
                    callbacks=[early_stopping,model_checkpoint])

# plot training history
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='training')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='validation')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Confusion Matrix Observations¶

The diagonal elements of the confusion matrix above represent the number of points for which the predicted label is equal to the true label, while off-diagonal elelements are those that are mislabeled by the model.

Let's determine how the model predicted the first 700 x_test actual labels¶

In [102]:
p_correct = 0
p_incorrect = 0
for i in range (699):
    a = np.argmax(y_test[i],axis = 0)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test[i].reshape(1, 128, 128, 3))
    pred = y_pred.argmax()
    if a == pred:
        p_correct = p_correct + 1
    else:
        p_incorrect = p_incorrect +1
print("Predicted Correctly ===> ", p_correct)
print("Predicted Incorrectly => ", p_incorrect)
print("% Predicted Correctly => ", p_correct / (p_correct + p_incorrect))

    

Predicted Correctly ===>  569
Predicted Incorrectly =>  130
% Predicted Correctly =>  0.8140200286123033

Conclusion:¶

  • The data was splitted 70% training and 30% testing. Then, test data was further split into 50/50 between test and validation.
  • During the model fit between training and validation, the accuracy score was 0.61 and validation loss at 1.05. Despite the validation loss be at 1.05, the training and validation loss line was not spreading apart (indication that the model is not overfitting).
  • Another model fit was performed between training and testing to determine how the model would perform in production.
  • The accuracy for Training and Testing was even better. Test accuracy scored 0.81 and test loss scored .54. A substantial improvement as compared to the train/validation.
  • Important also to mention is that the test/train loss lines were not moving apart indicating that the model is not overfitting.
  • To validate the model accuracy even further, a quick comparison between x_test actual and predicted was performed.
  • The results of this comparison is below:
